//- Server-Timing entries reported by the page's response headers.
//- Wrapped in the same .listing-card shell the other modernised pages
//- use, with a count chip in the header. The original template had a
//- malformed <thead>/<tr> structure; rebuilding it with a proper
//- thead/tbody pair lets data-sortable do its job. The card is omitted
//- entirely when no Server-Timing entries were sent — the empty-state
//- placeholder added clutter on the majority of pages where the
//- feature isn't wired up. Cells carry `data-title` so the responsive
//- mobile stack labels each value, and the duration is rendered through
//- `h.time.ms` so it shows up as "0 ms" like every other timing column
//- elsewhere in the report.
if timings.serverTimings && timings.serverTimings.length > 0
  - const serverTimingsCount = timings.serverTimings.length
  a#server-timings
  h3 Server timings
  p Timing data the server chose to expose through Server-Timing response headers on the main document — typically backend time, cache status or experiment flags.
  .listing-card
    .listing-card-header
      h3.listing-card-title Server timings
      span.listing-card-meta #{serverTimingsCount} #{serverTimingsCount === 1 ? 'entry' : 'entries'}
    .responsive
      table(data-sortable)
        thead
          tr
            th Name
            th.number Duration
            th Description
        tbody
          each serverTiming in timings.serverTimings
            tr
              td(data-title='Name')
                code.server-timing-name #{serverTiming.name}
              td.number(data-title='Duration', data-value=serverTiming.duration)= h.time.ms(serverTiming.duration)
              td.server-timing-desc(data-title='Description')
                if serverTiming.description
                  | #{serverTiming.description}
                else
                  | –
